I have never in my life written a review but I wanted to spread the good energy! I feel like i am the luckiest and happiest in the world to have found Dr Chang! He is a very genuine man who deeply cares about helping his patients. From the beginning his only goal was to help me feel confident again. You can really feel that your happiness is very important to him and you can trust him. Also, his assistant and entire staff was the best and most professional care I have ever received. So rare to experience an office full of such positive and hopeful energy.</Review>

< review>
I love Oceanside Dental Arts for a few reasons!

First and foremost, Diane!!! Best hygienist ever. She is thorough with a light touch and it feels more like a relaxing spa day than a dental cleaning. I also love chatting with her and catching up every six months. She is wonderful and I highly recommend her to anyone. My two sons had to join me for one cleaning (ages 6 and 7 at the time) and she was really awesome talking to them and including them in the conversation and making it fun instead of boring for them.

Secondly, Dr. Chang is great. He always stops by during my cleanings, checks everything out, is professional, explains things well, and also tells me what he is doing during the exam as he does it which I appreciate.

Finally, the office runs smoothly, and has great staff that enjoys it there. Appointments always feel like you get what you need and they spend the time with you needed, but also that they get you in and out relatively quickly. It's a fine balance but they have it down.

Oceanside Dental Arts is an upscale dental office that still feels friendly and homey. I always feel I'm in good hands, with honest assessments of my teeth, and no one trying to up-sale me on anything.</review>

<Text>The place is decorated very nicely, clean carpets throughout, which also keeps the area quiet.

Entertainment TVs everywhere, in front of both the main entrance and the examination seats. Could be even nicer of the tv is a bit higher there so it‚Äôs possible to see it while the chair is reclined.  In addition there is a monitor screen that can instantaneously display X-ray images and makes the office pretty much paperless.

The check in staff is pretty nice and I was seen by the equally friendly hygienist around my scheduled appointment time, who was pretty through with cleaning and polishing every corner. Best of all they offered me a pair of dark goggles to keep filter the light and keep splashing water out. Speaking of which the hygienists here usually only use a focused light rather than the large overhead light which further reduces glare. Dr. Stuart Chang also came in himself and explained in what ways my cleaning habits are good and what needs working on.

In conclusion Oceanside Dental Arts is a pretty modern looking and clean Dental clinic.It‚Äôs as modern as you can get with traditional dentistry around here.< /Text>< pics>

< review>
An injury, earned in my youth, decided to make a reappearance. Back surgery was required. My family is a member of Kaiser Permanente, an HMO, and I was sent to their surgery center at the Kaiser Permanente Los Angeles Medical Center.  (In Southern California there are about two dozen Kaiser Permanente medical facilities. Each has a specialty.) It is located on Sunset Boulevard just a few blocks from the Hollywood studios.

Since I am having trouble walking, a hospital volunteer sat me in a wheelchair and pushed me to reception. I was greeted, ID taken, and quickly moved to the surgery waiting room. The volunteer stayed until the nurse arrived.  A few minutes later I was laying in a hospital bed, gowned.

Every person I met showed courtesy and care. I never felt alone.

The laparoscopic surgery went well. I went home a couple of hours later.

This was the third operation I've had at the Los Angeles Medical Center. Each time, thank goodness, the procedure was successful, and the care and courtesy shown was all you could expect. Jessie Lee, my pre-op nurse, on behalf of the KP medical team, drop me a note thanking me for letting them take care of me. Wow. Never expected that.

Of course, everything is wheelchair accessible. My wife, who accompanied me, said the cafeteria was a long walk. Valet parking is available. The multi-story parking facility is located across the street from the hospital. Electric charging is available.< /review>

< review>
My stepfather recently stayed at Kaiser for a triple bypass. I've had years of experience with ailing loved ones as non-Kaiser facilities. As a result, I was dreading the experience, but it ended up being one of the most positive of our lives. The physicians, nurses, and all care-givers including staff who take lunch orders, are just spectacular. Everyone is so kind, helpful, and cheerful. Also, the hospital facility itself is so bright and open, infused with sunlight. A nurse in the cafeteria standing in line in front of my mom actually bought my mom dessert just to be kind. I don't know what makes this facility so unique but it should be a model for other organizations, including those outside of health care. Truly inspiring. And yes, my stepdad came through the procedure in great shape, owing to Kaiser's tremendous care.</review>

The second time was few years later at Kaiser.  I was seen immediately and left the hospital in less than 3 hours.  I would've probably left in an hour but they wanted to monitor me.

Kaiser is big on efficiency.  Therefore they operate like robots.  Everything is timed.  All the processes are timed. How long the doctor should spend time with you is timed.  Even nurses are timed.  The result is good service.< /text>

<review>I just got out of the hospital on the 23rd of March 2018.. I am a severe Type A hemophiliac who was rushed down to LA. I had a gall bladder that had 4 stones in it and was inflamed. I needed surgery to save my life. However I am so severe that operations can kill me cause I'll bleed to death. Normal medicine doesn't work on me... So the whole staff was working on my behalf to save my life. Dr. Michael Glowalla my hematologist was AWESOME. He has saved me now at least 4 times. The nurses on the 6th floor were amazing. The pain I was in made it so hard to move or do anything. But every nurse was aware of my condition and they all were really gentle with me so not to cause additional bleeding. The surgeons came in daily to give me updates on how they would tackle the impossible of trying to stop the bleeding and remove my gall bladder without touching any other organs and make them bleed as well. The whole staff was great. 6th floor nurses were awesome.. before and after surgery. As well as the ICU dept. Nurses. The professional treatment really made me happy and secure even knowing that I could die didn't give me pause for concern. The staff was like an orchestra and everyone had their place and part to play in the outcome of my survival. The Hospitals minister was AWESOME.. I saw him 3 times in my 2 and half week stay. He prayed over me and anointed me if I remember correctly. You cannot forget him.. a minister in a wheelchair paralyzed from the waist down with a smile that infects everyone around him. Kaiser does a great job taking care of patients and parents. Kaiser allowed my mom to stay in my room as well, so my mom never left my side. The operation was a success and i lived through the surgery. Kaisers Doctors all had a hand in my survival because they didn't rush me to surgery.. they treated me with antibiotics first and made sure I was well enough for surgery and knew all they could about my disease and the consequences if they made any mistakes. My life was in Kaiser doctors hands. I couldn't ask for better medical care. Everytime I had to urinate or needed ice and ice water the nursing staff were always very nice and kind and accommodating towards my needs. Anytime day or night they were there and answered my room calls within a few mins and if it was longer they reached out to me and said they were coming right after they finished their current job. I've never stayed that long in a hospital before with such serious health problems. Kaiser went above and beyond their duties.. they listened to me and always offered assistance in anything that I needed. Rehab staff was nice and were not pushy or mean. They encouraged me to move and walk longer each and every day they saw me. In the end I was one of the first successfully Severe Type A Hemophiliacs to survive a surgery of this kind. The inflamed gall bladder was taken out of me and not a single issue came from that. Kaiser Surgeons did their job very well. My surgeon had over a 1000 gall bladder removals. And was experienced and very confident even though he knew I could die on his operation table. He said he was gonna do everything he could to save my life and be careful and gentle and remove my gall bladder. And he did just that.. who could ask for more ? Kaiser doctors and staff prolonged my life and I get to live again. Granted I was swollen and in extreme pain but I was alive and survived. Even the wonderful wheelchair escort I was provided as I left the hospital bed was friendly and upbeat. A wonderful person .. she had me laughing and smiling. I just want to thank Kaiser for the tremendous effort they made to save my life and once again Dr. Michael Glowalla saved me again with his perfect plan to stop my bleeding and treat it for 11 days after my surgery. Way better than what my local hospital could do for me. So I am extremely grateful and blessed to still be here and I'm still recovering but I'm alive and well.. thanks to some wonderful people , nurses, doctors, specialists, surgeons, rehab, and Hospital Minister.. <Rating>5<//Rating><Review>I guess any hospital could get a bad review, as people's lives are in their hands. I have been in many hospitals, as I was not exactly the most careful person for most of my life. Normally, I just used emergency medical to cover the cost. I normally only have to go to the ICU every three or four years. I have come to learn that all of the hospitals are pretty much the same. I guess the real question is how do you plan to pay for your stay? My suggestion is do what is financially best for you, and if you can not decide then you better just let the paramedics take you to the closest hospital and pray that you make it to see the negative sides of a hospital. I do not care how the hospital lacks as long as I am still alive to write a review. Therefore, I give all hospitals a 5 that I have stayed at this far. They are not vacation resorts, instead they are their to do a job, and that job is to save your life at all cost. Sometimes this is not true for everyone, but if this is the closest hospital that your insurance provides for you, I suggest you take both the good and the bad. I am sure you can pick a hospital in Santa Monica or something, but you have to hope that you can make it there. Ambulance drivers will only transport you so far in an emergency. I suggest that you get to know the closest hospitals within your network and just go to that one.  If you cant chose just let them take you wherever and just hope you qualify for emergency medical. In all honesty LA County has the best doctors because they have every type of doctor on staff at a given moment, but the conditions are worst. Each hospital has its pros and cons.< /Review>< Name>
Kyle Turney</Name>

<Pics>None<//Pics>< Review>
This is my 3rd rendition of this review. I originally rated it 1-Star, then I upgraded it to 3-Stars, and now I am upgrading it once again to 5-Stars. My original 1-Star review almost entirely stemmed from the sheer frustration and heightened emotional state as a result of my wife being sick. But now that her and I have been in the hospital for over 1 day I've had time to clear my head and think rationally. Anyway, so here is my third and final (probably) review....

The first thing you will notice about this hospital is that it is located directly across the street from the Hollywood Scientology complex, which if you've seen the documentary "Going Clear" you'll find somewhat interesting.

Upon arrival I had a bit of trouble finding the parking structure but it's actually not that confusing, I'm just bad with directions. üòã The structure is 5 floors and there is ample parking for short visits as well as extended stays. The only downside is that there is a parking fee after a certain amount of time. It's not crazy expensive, but it's still an annoying factor to have at a hospital.

The hospital itself is incredibly expansive. For someone like me who has a bad sense of direction it is very easy to get lost here. So I advise you know exactly where you're going and if you have friends/family visiting be very specific with your directions.

The facility itself is clean for the most part and seems technologically advanced. All the doctors that I have interacted with thus far have been polite, thorough, informative, and empathetic. In addition, most of the nurses that I have interacted with thus far have been amazing! There have been a few that seemed to be in bad moods, but I can't fault them for that at all. I can speak specifically about the Emergency Department and Telemetry Department staff , and all I can say is that I'm thoroughly impressed (huge shout out to nurses Evelyn and Gerald in 7 West Telemetry: you're rock stars! Seriously, you're amazing nurses and I thank you so much for everything you did!) The level of care my wife has experienced thus far being here has been phenomenal. Everyone from the Janitors to the CNAs to the nurses to the doctors have been literally amazing. I feel 100% confident in the care that my wife is receiving and trust wholeheartedly that she will be taken care of in the best way possible.

This Kaiser branch has won me over. I was tentative at first, but the facility as a whole has exceeded all of my expectations for what a hospital and patient care should be. I definitely recommend this hospital.</Review>

1508199899623</date>
<rating>5</rating>< review>
I have been with Kaiser my whole life. As with any hospital, you will sometimes get bad doctors, but on the whole, I have been extremely satisfied with my experience there. I have a lot of medical conditions so see a lot of specialists and have been hospitalized several times. Plus my parents both use Kaiser too. We don't have to fight to get treatments like so many people I know do.

Kaiser was among the first hospital systems, let alone large ones like Kaiser, to get our records put on computer. So every time I see a doctor, that person can access whatever visit records or test results from my past they might need. And they use the computers to make sure there are no errors in giving medicine in the ER and hospital, since they have to scan your wrist band before giving you anything. The doctor types it into the computer in the first place to avoid handwriting errors, and the computer checks that there aren't any interactions among your medications with each new prescription.

I like that I can email my doctors, and now they have phone appointments for some medical issues. I can also view my lab tests online as soon as they become available. Mental health is also part of my coverage. Plus, I usually have to wait only 15 minutes or less to get taken to a bed in the ER at the Sunset facility, opposed to many hours at most hospitals.

No system is perfect, but this is about as close as we can get.< /review>

< Text>
I ship LTL and have been bouncing around between multiple logistics companies forever. The logistics companies would always give me a very low quote to start, but after a few shipments, the prices would get raised over and over again until I had to switch companies. I hated switching because finding a logistics company that understood how to handle large distribution centers with LTL was impossible and I would rack up late fee penalties. Auptix was next in line to try, I got great rates from them in the lanes they have high traffic. I didn't think much of this because all logistics companies had started out giving me low rates. However, I have been with them now for about a year now and I am still receiving these low rates! I have to say the reason I am writing this review is because my rep has been so great at helping me to find a solution to my specific shipping issues that I couldn't not let his bosses know how great of a job he is doing (Mandela B.). I had expressed my concerns to other reps before and they never took it as seriously as he did and I really appreciate that. The rates and the amazing rep is what's definitely keeping me with this company and I would recommend others to try Auptix, it really has reduced a lot of headaches for me. Lastly, I want to tell Mandela's bosses that he should ABSOLUTELY be promoted for his customer service skills, patience and determination, but I also don't want to lose him as my rep!</Text>

< review>
Rude. All around unpleasant. I walked in for a simple full acrylic set ($26 on their menu) 'Tim' didn't speak one word to me through the whole experience, but he spoke to the women around me while they were getting their nails done. Every time I pointed out a concern with my nail he'd tell me not to worry, it would be filed out....I'm a paying customer, if my nails aren't even you should be understanding and fix the issue. Instead no matter how many times I said 'oh...the acrylic doesn't completely cover this nail' or 'are you sure it's not supposed to cover my whole nail?' He'd just tell me it's all fine it will be filed out. Not to mention how frustrated he would get at ME because I accidentally touched the inside of the OPI nail light box (which I'd never used before so I had no idea there was a small lip) he would continuously HUFF as he fixed it...but at lease he 'fixed' it.
I left there after paying $35, yes THIRTY-FIVE DOLLARS, and went somewhere else to have my nails fixed because I had nail polish all over the underside, acrylic stuck under my nails and on my fingers and it felt so rushed like I was inconveniencing them.
I won't go back. I hope others don't waste their time. The Anderson Walmart has an AMAZING nail salon and amazing people who work there! Please don't waste your money at this nail salon.< /review>

<Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
A fabulous hole in the wall place at the crossroads of Beach and Artesia. I've never had Colombian food before but it will not be the last. Having ordered the Bandeja Paisa which was a mountain of meat on a bed of white rice, a side of the best beans ever, a sunny side egg, and half an avocado, the chicharron was fried to perfection and by far my favorite. Though it took 30 minutes for my food, it was well worth the wait. The server was kind and considerate.<//review>

This was one of the most amazing wine tasting experience I will remember for a lifetime!!
Initially the outside doesn't seem like much but once you enter the inside, let me tell you everything is perfect.
You can even taste wine in a large wine barrel but call in advance for reservations.
My friend and I went here a few weekends ago to celebrate our birthdays and Manny Lopez gave us the ultimate merryville experience!
He took us on the large barrel tour and allowed us to take pictures, as well as the quick tour of the back small barrels. He treated us like VIP and if we were napa natives would probably get a membership here. Manny was the epitome of customer service and deserves a raise! He is also an excellent photographer.  We really appreciate the extra mile he went to give us a good first experience in napa. This was our first wine tasting stop and honestly all the other wine tastings paled in comparison.
All around good service, clean and beautiful environment and amazing service.
The wine is amazing too.< /Review>

<pictures>None<//pictures>< Review>
We had our wedding reception this past May 2019 in Merryvale Winery's incredible Cask Room. It is lined by old giant wine barrels, lit with candles everywhere including giant candleabras on the table, and they can setup a reception table fit for a king and queen. We felt like we were dining in our own castle it was so stunning. The staff were so easy to work with. Casey helped us with the details and it was so simple. They work with a caterer so you don't have to search for one and the service was flawless. The food was incredible especially the short ribs that melted in your mouth and the ravioli with delicious, light, fresh tomato sauce. When someone gave a speech Chantelle magically would immediately turn down the music we were having played through the speaker system...she anticipated every need and we felt cared for every moment. All our guests were blown away by the beauty, food, and delicious wines!<//Review>

< Review>
Great customer service and great work.  My wife's car got shot up in the middle of the night.  My insurance agent said it would probably take a month or longer to fix because the car is brand new and it would be hard to find parts.  I took the car to Caliber Collision because they were pre-approved by my insurance company.  The staff was very nice and made check-in easy.  Enterprise picked me up from Caliber so getting a rental was easy too.  Richard called a few days later to give me an update and tell me they found two bullets in the bodywork, which I picked up and gave to the police.  Some of the parts were on national backorder but he called around and found them somewhere, not sure where.  The car was done a week after I dropped it off.  The car looks like nothing ever happened.  They even detailed it for us.  I paid my deductible to Caliber and took off with the car.  Getting your new car get shot up sucks, and the staff were really sympathetic to our situation. I'm VERY satisfied and would definitely use them again.</Review>

< text>
One of my favorite gambling spots.  Some of their slots are rip offs but some pretty much hit all the time.  I am digging Wheel of Fortune currently.  They have very reasonably priced food they will bring right to you at the slots.  Chicken strips and fries for instance or milk shakes and hamburgers.  Simple but yummy.  Restrooms are always clean and there's always security 24/7 to help with any concerns.  I left my phone in the ladies once, got all the way home ( about an hour) before i realized it, called them, and wow! They had it.  I had to prove it was mine by calling it, then unlocking it, and finally my id so they are on it. There is also a Bingo hall there and a handful of card tables.  I definitely recommend this Indian owned casino   for great evening of entertainment. And since reopening after covid masks are required as is a temperature check. And of social distancing.  There is plexi glass between slot machines.<//text>

< user>
101513405682403069692< /user>
< username>
Lindsey Amanda</username>
<date>1541816699978< /date><Rate>4</Rate>< Text>
Chicken Ranch is a funny name for a small, out of the way casino. The road leading to the casino is pretty tore up & a bit misleading. Just as you think something is wrong or maybe it's the wrong road, there it is! The casino is under construction as they are building a brand new bingo hall. They have moved the parking lot to across the street which, as of now is gravel. After finding your way in (main entrance is gated off) Chicken Ranch offers a variety of slots but no tables. It is a bit smokey & offers no non-smoking areas, except the bingo hall. There is a restaurant inside that offers very good food. It's a small cafe style, to sit g eat or they have finger foods available as well. They seem to be short staffed on waitresses often so don't count on one coming to offer a drink. Also only one ticket machine in the whole place or you can change a ticket at the cash cage where 2 ladies sit. If the place is packed which it usually is, plan on waiting in a line. Other than not having enough slots to accommodate all the players who visit it's great. Benches are available to those who just like to sit, free wifi, self serve coffee bar & free parking lot shuttle service are a few amenities offered here.</Text>

< text>
Ample parking and a decent casino make this bingo hall an amazing place to spend an evening with some friends for whenever you're in the mood for some gambling therapy.

Siu at the Bingo Hall gift shop is incredibly knowledgeable about her products and always has a smile on her face which makes buying snacks after not winning at Bingo much easier to stomach the loss.

The food from the restaurant is pretty good which is about all you can expect from a small-town casino--the specials, however, are where it's at if you need a decent meal at a decent price to keep your brain batteries charged for the continuous dobbing you'll more than likely be doing here at Chicken Ranch Casino.< /text>
